<section>
  <h2>How Lexi works</h2>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>1. Meet each word properly</h3>
      <p>Before a puzzle starts, every word you've never seen gets an
      illustrated word card — picture, definition, an example sentence that
      matches the picture, and connotation tags. No being blindsided by ten
      unknown words in a grid.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>2. Solve, don't flip</h3>
      <p>Clues are full sentences with the target word missing — recall in
      context, which is retrieval practice doing real work. Typo? Lexi notices
      near-misses and tells you instead of marking you wrong.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>3. The schedule runs itself</h3>
      <p>Spaced repetition decides which words appear in your next puzzle.
      Solve fast and the interval stretches; struggle and the word comes back
      sooner. You never grade yourself — your solving speed is the grade.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>What's inside</h2>
  <ul class="features">
    <li><strong>20,000 words</strong>, ordered roughly by rarity so you always learn the most useful next word</li>
    <li><strong>Synonym nuance:</strong> tap any two synonyms to read exactly how they differ</li>
    <li><strong>Collections that steer puzzles:</strong> save words, and puzzle generation prioritizes words with related meanings</li>
    <li><strong>Multiplayer, leaderboards, streaks, achievements</strong> and an activity heat map</li>
    <li><strong>Profiles:</strong> separate progress for you and your kid on the same iPad</li>
    <li><strong>Reminders tuned to your review backlog</strong>, not a fixed daily nag</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Who it's for (and not for)</h2>
  <p>Lexi is built for people who want a bigger English vocabulary and find
  flashcard apps hard to stick with: readers, writers, test preppers, and
  advanced ESL learners going from fluent to eloquent. It's English-only and
  iOS-only right now, and it currently teaches one primary sense per word —
  if you need multi-sense dictionary depth today, pair it with a good
  dictionary.</p>
  <p><a class="btn" href="{{ site.appstore }}">Get Lexi — free</a></p>
</section>

{% set posts = collections.posts | reverse %}
{% if posts.length > 0 %}
<section>
  <h2>From the blog</h2>
  <ul class="post-list">
    {% for p in posts.slice(0, 5) %}
    <li><a href="{{ p.url }}">{{ p.data.title }}</a> <span class="muted">{{ p.date | readableDate }}</span></li>
    {% endfor %}
  </ul>
</section>
{% endif %}

